                "content": [
                  {
                    "kind": "text",
                    "data": "Currently the chunker uses **fixed-size character splitting** with `RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter`:\n\n```python\nchunk_size=500, chunk_overlap=50,\nseparators=[\"\\n## \", \"\\n### \", \"\\n\\n\", \"\\n\", \". \", \" \"]\n```\n\nIt tries to split at markdown headers first (`##`, `###`), then paragraphs, then sentences, then words — but ultimately it just aims for ~500 character chunks regardless of semantic meaning.\n\n**The problem with this approach:**\n- A section about \"routing\" might get split into 3 chunks, losing context\n- A chunk might contain the tail of one topic and the start of another\n- Headers get separated from their content\n\n**Better approaches:**\n\n1. **Header-based (semantic sections)** — split at `# / ## / ###` boundaries, keeping each section as one chunk (with max size limit). Each chunk = one complete topic.\n\n2. **Topic-aware** — parse the markdown structure, keep header + its body together, and only split further if a section exceeds max size.\n\n3. **Hybrid** — split by headers first, then if a section is too large, subdivide it using the recursive character splitter.\n\nOption 3 is the best for our use case. Want me to rewrite the chunker to be header-aware? It would:\n- Parse markdown headers to identify sections\n- Keep `## Section Title` + its body as one chunk\n- Only split large sections (>1000 chars) further using character splitting\n- Preserve the section title as a prefix in sub-chunks for context"
                  }
                ],
                "meta": {
                  "timestamp": 1781780303
                }
              }
            },
